SIMPLE: stampede
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Stampede
<hw>Stam*pede"</hw> <pr>(st⟦acr⟧m*p⟦emac⟧d")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[Sp. <ets>estampida</ets> (in America) a stampede,
<ets>estampido</ets> a crackling, akin to <ets>estampar</ets> to stamp,
of German origin. See <er>Stamp</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A wild, headlong scamper, or running away, of a number
of animals; usually caused by fright; hence, any sudden flight or
dispersion, as of a crowd or an army in consequence of a
panic.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Any sudden unconcerted moving or acting together of
a number of persons, as from some common impulse; <as>as, a
<ex>stampede</ex> to the gold regions; a <ex>stampede</ex> in a
convention</as>; a <ex>stampede</ex> toward U. S. bonds in the credit
markets.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><q>She and her husband would join in the general
<qex>stampede</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>W. Black.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- p. 1402 pr=VMG --></p>

<p><ent>Stampede</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Stampede
<hw>Stam*pede"</hw> <pr>(st⟦acr⟧m*p⟦emac⟧d")</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos>
<def>To run away in a panic; -- said of droves of cattle, horses, etc.,
also of armies.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stampede</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Stampede
<hw>Stam*pede"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To disperse by causing sudden
fright, as a herd or drove of animals.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Stamper</ent>⟦br⟧
